In `src/app.ts`, the `handleUpload` function loops over the selected files calling `await api.upload(path, file)` sequentially. If any single upload fails (network error, 413 too large, 400 invalid name), the entire loop aborts via unhandled rejection, the remaining uploads are silently skipped, the input is not cleared, and the user gets no feedback. Fix: wrap each per-file `api.upload` call in its own try/catch (or use `Promise.allSettled` if you convert to parallel — but sequential is fine and preserves ordering). Track the failed file names in a local array. After the loop, regardless of partial failures: (1) clear `uploadInput.value` (so the same file can be re-selected); (2) call `render()` to refresh the listing; (3) if any uploads failed, surface them via the status footer (e.g., `statusEl.textContent = 'Uploaded N file(s); failed: a.txt, b.txt'`). If all succeeded, leave the success-path status alone (the re-render will refresh it via renderBrowse/renderSearch). Do NOT change the upload endpoint, the input clearing, or the re-render on full success. Verification: `npm test` passes (the existing 'uploads each selected file' test still passes); the test-writing phase may add a test where one of several uploads fails (mock the first to resolve and the second to reject) and assert the remaining file is still uploaded, the input is cleared, and the failure is surfaced.

